You can&#39;t use 2 different types for the keys of a map. The map defines 2 type parameters, `Map&lt;K ,V&gt;`, and these are used in `put(K, V)` and `V get(K)`. Your `K` is `Decorator` and your `V` is `String`. Your `map.get(3)` call will always return `null` because a `Decorator` can&#39;t be equal to an `int` (not without violating the contract of `Object.equals`).

What you can do, and this is a normal thing to do, is use `Delegator`&#39;s `int i` as an effective key. You need to fulfill 2 criteria:
1. `@Override` the `equals(Object)` method, which is used to determine which keys are duplicates, with that of your contained instance.
2. `@Override` the `hashCode()` method (always do so when overriding `equals()`), which is used by `HashMap`, with that of your contained instance.

This is called *delegation* - you delegate the functionality/behavior from the containing type to that of the contained type. Here, we are delegating the calls to `Decorator` to `int i`.

```
    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Integer.hashCode(i); // Decorator&#39;s hash code is i&#39;s hash code
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (obj == this) { // this is just an optimization, but not really needed in this case
            return true;
        }
        if (!(obj instanceof Decorator)) {
            return false;
        }
        final Decorator other = (Decorator) obj;
        return i == other.i; // Decorators are equal if their i is equal
    }
```

Now you can do
```
        map.put(new Decorator(3, &quot;some string&quot;), &quot;some value&quot;);
        System.out.println(map.get(new Decorator(3, &quot;&quot;)));
```
because only the `int` field is used to search the map.

