Browser and performance logging only captures whatever is logged to the console and connection metadata in Chrome (at least, at the time of this writing). To actually get the contents of a fetch request I found some JS ([source][1]) to intercept all fetch requests and log the contents to the console which I could then access in browser logs. Total overkill, but hey it works.

```javascript
const { fetch: originalFetch } = window;
window.fetch = async (...args) =&gt; {
  let [resource, config] = args;

  let response = await originalFetch(resource, config);

  response
    .clone()
    .json()
    .then((data) =&gt; console.log(&quot;fetch response:&quot; + JSON.stringify(data)));

  return response;
};
```

